	<li id="comment-20377">
	<p>Great page, thanks for this &#8211; I&#039;ll point some of my more paranoid friends in its direction.</p>
<p>One more point though ,that wasn&#039;t covered.  I haven&#039;t read all the comments, so apologies if someone has already brought this up:  Applications that seem harmless can act as data miners and, as I understand it, can access your friends details as well.</p>
<p>So, while I may not have chosen to add the &quot;Send underwater lovehearts&quot; application, it can nevertheless access certain aspects of my information.</p>
<p>This can be remedied by blocking your information in the settings described in the post or by blocking the application entirely.  The latter also means if other friends invite you to the application (and I&#039;ve had over a dozen invites for the same application in one day before) you don&#039;t get the same invites popping up again and again and again.</p>
<p>Thanks!</p>
	<p><cite>Comment by <a href='http://kevin.campbellwright.co.uk/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Kevin Campbell-Wrigh</a> &#8212; February 16, 2009 @ <a href="#comment-20377">12:16 am</a></cite> </p>
